{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413036"},"attributes":{"position":5,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:51:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:51:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261097"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:50:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":7,"questionsAnswered":6,"marksTotal":6,"marksAttainable":6,"marksAttempted":6,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:51:34+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.17,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"14337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14337"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.15,0.35,0.08,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7032"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40235"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2299"},{"type":"tags","id":"3586"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34678"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent, concerned about the development of pubic hair and body odour over the past eight months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. There is a family history of polycystic ovarian syndrome in a maternal cousin. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her height is on the 85th percentile and weight on the 95th percentile. Physical examination reveals Tanner stage 1 breasts and Tanner stage 2 pubic hair. Mild facial acne and apocrine body odour are noted. There is no clitoromegaly or posterior labial fusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBone age: 9 years\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlasma 17-hydroxyprogesterone: 4.8 nmol/L (\u0026lt;6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETestosterone: 1.4 nmol/L (\u0026lt;1)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDHEAS: 3.5 \u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt;1.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOestradiol: 35 pmol/L (\u0026lt;50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELH: 1.5 units/L (0.5-2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFSH: 1.2 units/L (0.8-1.7)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-classical congenital adrenal hyperplasia","Polycystic ovarian syndrome","Premature adrenarche","Adrenal adenoma","Idiopathic central precocious puberty"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this seven-year-old girl is \u003Cstrong\u003Epremature adrenarche\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by the early onset of adrenal androgen production, typically manifesting as the development of pubic hair, body odour, and sometimes mild acne before the age of eight in girls or nine in boys. The key features supporting this diagnosis are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. The presence of pubic hair and body odour without breast development (Tanner stage 1 breasts).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Mildly elevated androgens (DHEAS and testosterone) with normal gonadotropins (LH and FSH) and oestradiol levels. This pattern suggests increased adrenal androgen production without activation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Bone age slightly advanced but within two years of chronological age, which is typical for premature adrenarche.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-classical congenital adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to premature adrenarche, but it typically involves elevated 17-hydroxyprogesterone levels, which are normal in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovarian syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (PCOS) is not typically diagnosed in pre-pubertal girls. While there is a family history of PCOS, and some features (like mild androgen elevation) can be similar, the absence of menstrual irregularities and the patient\u0027s young age make this diagnosis less likely at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more severe virilisation and much higher androgen levels. The mild elevation of androgens in this case is not consistent with an adrenal tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic central precocious puberty\u003C/strong\u003E involves early activation of the entire hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis. This would typically present with breast development (which is absent here) and elevated gonadotropins (LH and FSH), which are normal in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPremature adrenarche is generally considered a benign variant of normal development. However, these children should be monitored as they may be at increased risk for metabolic syndrome and PCOS later in life. Management typically involves reassurance and monitoring for normal progression of puberty.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Premature adrenarche is characterised by early development of pubic hair and body odour without other signs of puberty.","Elevated DHEAS and testosterone levels, with normal gonadotropins, are typical biochemical findings in premature adrenarche.","Bone age advancement is common in premature adrenarche but usually less than two years ahead of chronological age."],"references":["Rosenfield RL. Normal and Premature Adrenarche. Endocr Rev. 2021 Nov 16;42(6):783-814. doi: 10.1210/endrev/bnab009. PMID: 33788946; PMCID: PMC8599200."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40235"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14337"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40235"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T14:56:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-28T11:15:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7032"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54705"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrino